How can I use Java code to extract two adjectives from a given sentence and provide example sentences for each adjective? 
In addition, could you provide a JSON dataset of adjectives used to describe emotions and their corresponding brief descriptions? Here is a sample HTML page displaying this dataset in a readable format:
```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>Emotion Adjectives Dataset</title>
	<style>
		table, th, td {
			border: 1px solid black;
			border-collapse: collapse;
		}
		th, td {
			padding: 10px;
			text-align: center;
		}
		th {
			background-color: #f2f2f2;
		}
	</style>
</head>
<body>
	<h1>Emotion Adjectives Dataset</h1>
	<table style="width:50%">
		<tr>
			<th>Adjective</th>
			<th>Description</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Angry</td>
			<td>Feeling or showing anger or strong resentment</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Sad</td>
			<td>Feeling or showing sorrow; unhappy</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Happy</td>
			<td>Feeling or showing pleasure or contentment</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Excited</td>
			<td>Feeling or showing excitement; thrilled</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Anxious</td>
			<td>Feeling or showing worry, nervousness, or unease</td>
		</tr>
	</table>
</body>
</html>
```
As for generating the HTML table using Java code, you can use libraries such as JSoup to parse the HTML and create the table dynamically. Here is an example code snippet:
```
import org.jsoup.Jsoup;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Document;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Element;
import org.jsoup.select.Elements;
public class HTMLTableParser {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		String html = "<html><head><title>Emotion Adjectives Dataset</title><style>table, th, td {border: 1px solid black;border-collapse: collapse;}th, td {padding: 10px;text-align: center;}th {background-color: #f2f2f2;}</style></head><body><h1>Emotion Adjectives Dataset</h1><table style='width:50%'><tr><th>Adjective</th><th>Description</th></tr><tr><td>Angry</td><td>Feeling or showing anger or strong resentment</td></tr><tr><td>Sad</td><td>Feeling or showing sorrow; unhappy</td></tr><tr><td>Happy</td><td>Feeling or showing pleasure or contentment</td></tr><tr><td>Excited</td><td>Feeling or showing excitement; thrilled</td></tr><tr><td>Anxious</td><td>Feeling or showing worry, nervousness, or unease</td></tr></table></body></html>";
		Document doc = Jsoup.parse(html);
		Element table = doc.select("table").first();
		Elements rows = table.select("tr");
		for (Element row : rows) {
			Elements cells = row.select("td");
			for (Element cell : cells) {
				System.out.print(cell.text() + "\t");
			}
			System.out.println();
		}
	}
}
```

To achieve the tasks you mentioned, we need to address two separate requirements: extracting adjectives from a sentence using Java and creating a JSON dataset of adjectives describing emotions, along with an HTML representation of that dataset.

### Part 1: Extracting Adjectives from a Sentence Using Java

To extract adjectives from a sentence in Java, you can use the Stanford CoreNLP library, which provides a suite of natural language processing tools. Here's how you can extract adjectives:

```java
import edu.stanford.nlp.pipeline.*;
import edu.stanford.nlp.ling.CoreAnnotations;
import edu.stanford.nlp.ling.CoreLabel;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Properties;

public class AdjectiveExtractor {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String text = "The beautiful garden was full of vibrant flowers.";

        // Set up the pipeline properties
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.setProperty("annotators", "tokenize,ssplit,pos");

        // Build the pipeline
        StanfordCoreNLP pipeline = new StanfordCoreNLP(props);

        // Create a document object
        CoreDocument document = new CoreDocument(text);

        // Annotate the document
        pipeline.annotate(document);

        // Extract adjectives
        int adjectiveCount = 0;
        for (CoreLabel token : document.tokens()) {
            String pos = token.get(CoreAnnotations.PartOfSpeechAnnotation.class);
            if ("JJ".equals(pos)) {
                System.out.println("Adjective: " + token.word());
                adjectiveCount++;
            }
            if (adjectiveCount == 2) {
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Part 2: JSON Dataset of Emotion Adjectives

Here's a sample JSON dataset of adjectives used to describe emotions:

```json
{
    "emotions": [
        {
            "adjective": "Angry",
            "description": "Feeling or showing anger or strong resentment"
        },
        {
            "adjective": "Sad",
            "description": "Feeling or showing sorrow; unhappy"
        },
        {
            "adjective": "Happy",
            "description": "Feeling or showing pleasure or contentment"
        },
        {
            "adjective": "Excited",
            "description": "Feeling or showing excitement; thrilled"
        },
        {
            "adjective": "Anxious",
            "description": "Feeling or showing worry, nervousness, or unease"
        }
    ]
}
```

### HTML Representation of the JSON Dataset

You can parse this JSON and display it in an HTML table using JavaScript and libraries like `jQuery` or `Vanilla JS`. Here's how you can do it with a simple script:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Emotion Adjectives Dataset</title>
    <style>
        table, th, td {
            border: 1px solid black;
            border-collapse: collapse;
        }
        th, td {
            padding: 10px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        th {
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Emotion Adjectives Dataset</h1>
    <table id="emotionTable" style="width:50%">
        <tr>
            <th>Adjective</th>
            <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <script>
        const emotions = [
            { "adjective": "Angry", "description": "Feeling or showing anger or strong resentment" },
            { "adjective": "Sad", "description": "Feeling or showing sorrow; unhappy" },
            { "adjective": "Happy", "description": "Feeling or showing pleasure or contentment" },
            { "adjective": "Excited", "description": "Feeling or showing excitement; thrilled" },
            { "adjective": "Anxious", "description": "Feeling or showing worry, nervousness, or unease" }
        ];

        const table = document.getElementById('emotionTable');
        emotions.forEach(emotion => {
            const row = table.insertRow();
            const cell1 = row.insertCell(0);
            const cell2 = row.insertCell(1);
            cell1.textContent = emotion.adjective;
            cell2.textContent = emotion.description;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code uses JavaScript to dynamically generate an HTML table from the JSON data, which can be displayed in a web browser.
